"Lee J., Kim I.S.","Microbial community in seawater reverse osmosis and rapid diagnosis of membrane biofouling",2011,"Desalination","273","1",,"118","126",,,10.1016/j.desal.2010.12.005,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-79953036630&partnerID=40&md5=198dbafd7903802567363bb74ce1141d","Center for Seawater Desalination Plant, Gwangju Institute of Science and Technology (GIST), 261 Cheomdan-gwagiro, Buk-gu, Gwangju 500-712, South Korea","Lee, J., Center for Seawater Desalination Plant, Gwangju Institute of Science and Technology (GIST), 261 Cheomdan-gwagiro, Buk-gu, Gwangju 500-712, South Korea; Kim, I.S., Center for Seawater Desalination Plant, Gwangju Institute of Science and Technology (GIST), 261 Cheomdan-gwagiro, Buk-gu, Gwangju 500-712, South Korea","Due to the acceleration of global warming and the stress that population growth has placed on the global water supply, seawater reverse osmosis (SWRO) desalination is arising as a promising technology to overcome the stress placed on current water resources. However, the biofouling of RO membranes is a common problem, as it causes flux decline, demands frequent cleanings, and consumes high energy, resulting in a shortened lifespan of the system. In an attempt to address these issues, detailed knowledge of the microbial bacteria present, which have a strong correlation between biofilm community structure and operational problems, is ultimately expected to lead to greater control of biofouling. Furthermore, a more rapid diagnosis of biofilm bacteria in SWRO processes is required for faster process feedback. In this study, previous approaches that have been proposed for understanding, diagnosing, and predicting biofouling are reviewed. Finally, the future outlook towards controlling biofouling in SWRO is discussed. © 2010 Elsevier B.V.","Biofouling; Microbial community; Seawater reverse osmosis","Common problems; Community structures; Flux decline; High energy; Life span; Membrane biofouling; Microbial communities; On currents; Operational problems; Population growth; RO membrane; Seawater reverse osmosis; Strong correlation; Bacteriology; Biofilms; Biofouling; Desalination; Global warming; Population statistics; Seawater; Water filtration; Water resources; Water supply; Reverse osmosis; biofilm; biofouling; community structure; desalination; membrane; microbial community; osmosis; seawater; Bacteria (microorganisms)",,,,,,"Bouwer, H., Integrated water management: emerging issues and challenges (2000) Agric. Water Manage., 45, pp. 217-228; Fritzmann, C., Lowenberg, J., Wintgens, T., Melin, T., State-of-the-art of reverse osmosis desalination (2007) Desalination, 216, pp. 1-76; Kim, S., Cho, D., Lee, M.-S., Oh, B.S., Kim, J.H., Kim, I.S., SEAHERO R&D program and key strategies for the scale-up of a seawater reverse osmosis (SWRO) system (2009) Desalination, 238, pp. 1-9; Abdul Azis, P.K., Al-Tisan, I., Sasikumar, N., Biofouling potential and environmental factors of seawater at a desalination plant intake (2001) Desalination, 135, pp. 69-82; Vrouwenvelder, J.S., van der Kooij, D., Diagnosis of fouling problems of NF and RO membrane installations by a quick scan (2003) Desalination, 153, pp. 121-124; Vrouwenvelder, J.S., Manolarakis, S.A., van der Hoek, J.P., van Paassen, J.A.M., van der Meer, W.G.J., van Agtmaal, J.M.C., Prummel, H.D.M., van Loosdrecht, M.C.M., Quantitative biofouling diagnosis in full scale nanofiltration and reverse osmosis installations (2008) Water Res., 42, pp. 4856-4868; Shahalam, A.M., Al-Harthy, A., Al-Zawhry, A., Feed water pretreatment in RO systems: unit processes in the middle east (2002) Desalination, 150, pp. 235-245; Alawadhi, A.A., Pretreatment plant design - key to a successful reverse osmosis desalination plant (1997) Desalination, 110, pp. 1-10; Cottrell, M.T., Kirchman, D.L., Community composition of marine bacterioplankton determined by 16S rRNA gene clone libraries and fluorescence in situ hybridization (2000) Appl. Environ. Mic